{
  "answer": "**Charles Comte defines \"occupation des choses\" (the occupation of things) at the outset of Chapter 4 of *Traité de la propriété: VOL I*, titled \"De l'occupation des choses\" (On the occupation of things).**[^1]\n\nThere, he states: \"The act of taking possession of a thing that has no master, with the intention of appropriating it, has been considered at all times by jurists as one of the principal means of acquiring property.\"[^1] The entire chapter elaborates on this concept as a foundational mode of property acquisition, applicable to nations, families, and individuals, distinguishing it from possession or other means, and rooted in natural human needs and sentiments rather than convention or legislation.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété: VOL I*, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/04-de-loccupation-des-choses/translation/#p-ab8596).\n[^2]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété: VOL I*, [chapter](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/04-de-loccupation-des-choses/translation/).",
